### L121–L145 product-design batch summary (added)

Twenty-five standalone Phase-3 product-design artifacts covering the screen-by-screen UX of OPENGEM World Dashboard. Each opinionated: ASCII wireframes where layout-relevant, decisions with rationale, [[backlinks]], 1,377–2,137 words each.

Headline decisions:

- **Top nav (L121)**: six slots — `World / Countries / Indicators / Scenarios / Forecasts / Ledger`. URL convention: `/c/{iso3}`, `/i/{slug}`, `/s/{pack}`, `/f/{ind}/{iso3}/{horizon}`, `/v/{date}` for vintage.
- **World home (L122)**: Headline + Strip + Stream pattern; 10-second world readout.
- **Country / Indicator / Scenario / Forecast pages (L123–L126)**: hero + strip + drilldown drawers, with right-edge methodology slide-outs. Forecast page emphasizes vintage rewind as the defining feature.
- **Provenance drawer (L132)**: mandatory on every chart, enforced by CI lint; replay-and-diff is the trust mechanism.
- **Leaderboard (L133) + Track-record (L134)**: configurable scoreboards with OPENGEM compared honestly against WEO, OECD EO, FRB SEP, Cleveland Nowcast, GDPNow + naive baselines.
- **Methodology (L135)**: 11-section template enforced by CI; ≥3 known-limitations required; "NOT PUBLISHED FOR FORECAST USE" stamp for V&V-failed packs.
- **Pricing (L138)**: three-tier (Free / Pro / Team) with calibration scorecard rendered ON the pricing page — the load-bearing brand move.
- **Onboarding (L139)**: 3 steps (watchlist / email / role); never blocking; magic-link or GitHub OAuth.
- **Theme default (L145)**: Terminal Orange (Bloomberg-coded dark canvas + #FF6F00 brand). Editorial FT-pink and Playful OWID-blue available as user toggles.
- **Mobile (L142)**: six-slot nav collapses to four (World / Explore / Ledger / Search); strips become horizontal-scroll tiles; drawers become bottom sheets.
- **Embeds (L144)**: three sizes (400×400 square / 728×240 banner / 300×600 tall); single-script JS contract with static-image fallback for iframe-blocked hosts.
- **Empty states (L140) + Error/degraded (L141)**: terse voice rules; honest staleness banners; public `/status` page.
- **Search (L128)**: ⌘K command bar with three modes (search / `>` command / `/` URL); ~50 commands enumerated across 8 categories.

### L211–L230 thematic indicator pages summary (added)

Twenty standalone product-design artifacts for thematic dashboard pages. Each picks structure, visualizations, data sources; all carry [[backlinks]]; all 1,400–2,000 words. Three pages with the strongest "Bloomberg-killer" potential — judged by (a) breadth of incumbent gap, (b) feature distinctiveness, (c) downstream API/MCP queryability:

1. **L213 Recession probability page** — cross-country grid + BMA across 4 models + vintaged backtest + calibration plot on every row. NY Fed has US-only; nobody has the cross-country, sortable, MCP-queryable version. This is the page an LLM agent queries 100× per day.
2. **L218 Trade balance + bilateral matrix** — the 30×30 bilateral-matrix UX with time-scrub and click-to-drill, plus capital-flow attribution. No public dashboard has this; every macro shop wants it.
3. **L230 Long-horizon scenarios — the compound scenario tool** — letting the user pick population from one SSP, productivity from another. No public dashboard offers SSP composability; this is a Y2 milestone but the feature is unique.

Honorable mentions: L211 shock library (impulse-response on demand for non-pros), L226 supply-chain bottleneck page (PortWatch is dramatically underexploited), L228 conflict tracker "priced-in?" widget (trader alpha).

Adapter gaps discovered across the batch (organized by priority — count of pages that need each):

**TIER 1 — highest leverage (4+ pages depend):**
- BIS adapter (`opengem-data-bis`) — REER, property prices, sovereign credit, rates. Named in roster, not built. Unblocks L215, L217, L220, L224.
- ECB SDW adapter (`opengem-data-ecb`) — euro-area FCI components, mortgage rates, term spreads, wage trackers. Unblocks L213, L214, L215, L219, L220.
- IMF SDMX extensions (`opengem-data-imf`) — DOTS, BOP, Fiscal Monitor, Article-IV PDF extraction. Named in roster, partial. Unblocks L212, L216, L218, L224.
- GDELT 2.0 (`opengem-data-gdelt`) — already named, not built. Unblocks L225, L228, L229.
- CME / ICE settle adapters (`opengem-data-cme`, `opengem-data-ice`) — futures term structure for oil, gas, ag, metals. Unblocks L211, L215, L221, L227.

**TIER 2 — single-page unlock with high page importance:**
- DTCC weekly CDS file (`opengem-data-dtcc`) — sovereign CDS spine. Unblocks L216.
- IIASA SSP database (`opengem-data-iiasa`) — long-horizon scenario spine. Unblocks L222, L230.
- UN Population Division (`opengem-data-unpop`) — UN WPP 2024. Unblocks L222, L223, L230.
- EIA + IEA (`opengem-data-eia`, `opengem-data-iea`) — energy spot + inventory + STEPS/APS/NZE. Unblocks L211, L221, L230.
- Open Sanctions (`opengem-data-opensanctions`) — sanctions consolidated. Unblocks L216, L225.
- PortWatch + IMF Trade Tracker (`opengem-data-portwatch`, `opengem-data-imf-tt`) — first named, second new. Unblocks L218, L226.
- IMF Article-IV PDF extractor (`opengem-data-imf-art4-extract`) — LLM-mediated PDF extraction of DSA + downside scenarios. Unblocks L212, L224.

**TIER 3 — high-quality single-page additions:**
- FHFA, Case-Shiller, NAR, Freddie Mac PMMS (housing) — L220.
- V-Dem + Polity + Freedom House (political-risk substrate) — L227.
- UCDP + ACLED + UNHCR (conflict) — L228.
- BLS extension for JOLTS / ECI / demographic cuts — L219.
- Eurostat (`opengem-data-eurostat`) — EU-wide labor, housing, HPI, HICP — L214, L219, L220.
- Wittgenstein Centre multidim demographic projections — L223, L230.
- EDGAR emissions + NGFS scenarios — L222, L230.
- ETS prices (EU ETS, RGGI, CCA, China) — L221, L222.

The thematic-page work surfaced ~35 distinct adapter / data-source gaps. **The single highest-leverage build is the BIS adapter** — it unblocks four pages immediately and is a known-quality data source. The second-highest-leverage build is **the IMF SDMX extension** to handle DOTS + BOP + Article-IV PDFs, which unblocks three of the heaviest pages.

### L021–L030 license landscape summary (added)

GREEN sources OPENGEM should ingest immediately:
- **GDELT 2.0 + GKG** (L021) — global event + tone, 15-min cadence, free-use with citation, BigQuery + raw-zip + DOC API. This is the single richest open geopolitical substrate on Earth.
- **UCDP** (L026) — CC-BY-4.0, the cleanest academic conflict dataset, free API with token (Feb 2026+), 18 datasets, 1946+ depth. The GREEN substitute for ACLED that doesn't require an EULA dance.
- **Caldara-Iacoviello GPR family** (L024) — GREEN academic, monthly + daily + country-specific (44 countries), 125-year historical. Already ingested via `opengem-data-gpr`; five extensions identified (GPRD, GPR-C heatmap, GPR-SR breakdown, AI-GPR cross-validate, forecast feature).

Honorable mentions also GREEN and worth queueing right after:
- **POLECAT + ICEWS-legacy + Cline Center Phoenix** (L023/L025) — Harvard Dataverse CC0 + Illinois Data Bank open. Full event-stream backbone 1945→present once we apply the CAMEO→PLOVER crosswalk.
- **V-Dem v16** (L027) — Bayesian-credible-interval democracy indices, 1789→present, 531 indicators × 251 indices × 202 polities. License needs explicit clarification but is treated as free academic.
- **World Bank WGI** (L030) — CC-BY-4.0, governance indicators with unobserved-components-model SEs.

Licensing landmines:
- **ACLED** (L022) — YELLOW EULA. Bans "dashboards that compete with or create functional substitutes for ACLED's own platforms." OPENGEM can publish derived/transformative aggregates with attribution; cannot republish raw rows; should keep ACLED-derived metrics in free-tier only at v1 (no paid API surface) until a commercial agreement is negotiated. GDELT+UCDP+POLECAT must be a working fallback.
- **OpenSanctions** (L028) — YELLOW CC-BY-NC. Free non-commercial; paid commercial license required the moment a paying customer hits an OpenSanctions-backed endpoint. Pre-launch task: written interpretation from OpenSanctions for OPENGEM's open-source-with-paid-tier model.
- **Stratfor / Geopolitical Futures / EIU / Maplecroft / Fitch / PRS** (L029, L030) — RED for substrate ingestion. Cite as benchmarks on the L133 forecast leaderboard, never reproduce their numbers.
- **WikiLeaks gifiles** (L029) — Legally radioactive for systematic republication. Zero ingestion; link out only if absolutely necessary.
- **Bellingcat published articles** (L029) — YELLOW. Citation/fair-use OK; mirroring not. Toolkit is CC-BY-ND; code repos MIT.
- **V-Dem and Freedom House** (L027, L030) — License clarification pending; treated GREEN with conservative attribution.

The single most strategically important finding: **POLECAT on Harvard Dataverse provides a GREEN, CC0-licensed substitute for ~95% of what ACLED gives us**, with weekly cadence, ML-coded events on the PLOVER ontology, 2018-present coverage. This means OPENGEM's open-public-substrate promise survives even if ACLED licensing tightens.

### L031–L045 macro-forecasting adoption summary (added)

A-grade adoptions (build directly into Block I/II):
- **`statsmodels.tsa.statespace.DynamicFactorMQ`** (L032) — Chad Fulton's NY-Fed-equivalent class. BSD-3. The L3 DFM workhorse. **The single highest-grade pick of L031–L045 and arguably of the whole macro-forecasting block.** Drop-in adoption with zero re-implementation.
- **`statsmodels.tsa` + `tsa.vector_ar` + `statespace` family** (L035) — BSD-3 substrate for everything time-series.
- **PyMC + NumPyro JAX backend** (L036) — Apache-2.0. The Bayesian extension layer for BVAR / TVP-VAR / hierarchical scenario probability.
- **`bank-of-england/forecast_evaluation`** (L041) — MIT. Surprise win: Diebold-Mariano + Mincer-Zarnowitz + revision predictability + density-forecast PIT in one Python package, written by the BoE forecasting team. Adopt as `opengem-vv` backbone.
- **World Bank `wbgapi` + CC-BY 4.0 data layer** (L042) — MIT code, the most permissive data license in macro. Adopt as `opengem-data-wb`.
- **ECB SPF + Philly Fed SPF + OECD EO + IMF WEO + World Bank GEP** (L043) — full consensus-comparison stack, all free, no license blockers.
- **Nixtla `statsforecast` + `mlforecast` + `hierarchicalforecast`** (L044) — Apache-2.0. L3 baselines + ML variant + cross-aggregate reconciliation.

B-grade adoptions (build in Block II):
- **Cleveland Fed inflation nowcast methodology** (L033) — replicate Knotek-Zaman 2017 in Python; ~1 week of work.
- **`statsmodels.tsa.statespace.MLEModel` for custom states** (L037) — wrap MIDAS, FAVAR, TVP variants.
- **BGVAR R package via rpy2** (L038) — GPL-3 R, no Python equivalent at this maturity; for L2 cross-country scenarios at annual cadence.
- **PyFRB/US** (L039) — public-domain US-federal work, Python, May 2026. Block II curated-scenario wrapper for US monetary-policy counterfactuals.
- **IMF SDMX 3.0 data adapter** (L040) — `sdmx1` Python lib + custom retry/vintage layer.
- **CCBS Mumtaz handbook code** (L041) — MATLAB; read for spec, translate one BVAR example to PyMC as proof.
- **World Bank `MFMod-ModelFlow`** (L042) — CC0; developing-country structural model fill.
- **Nixtla `neuralforecast`** (L044) — Apache-2.0; one-sprint Block II experiment vs DFM baseline.
- **openICPSR / AEA replication pipeline** (L045) — quarterly scan + reproduce-and-port for top papers.

Disqualifying license issues found in L031–L045:
- **None for the A-grade picks.** Everything we want to actually adopt is BSD / MIT / Apache-2.0 / CC-BY 4.0 / public-domain.
- **GPL-3 for BGVAR** (L038) — we mitigate by using BGVAR as a subprocess-invoked R dependency (rsync/SSH precedent: subprocess calls do not virally license the caller). BGVAR adoption is behind a feature flag so the rest of OPENGEM remains pure Apache-2.0.
- **GPL-3 for Dynare** (L034) — same posture; called as external tool, model files segregated.
- **Closed-source for TimeGPT** (L044), **Consensus Economics** (L043), **GDPNow code** (L031), **Cleveland Fed code** (L033), **Now-Casting.com** (L033), **COMPASS/MAPS/EASE** (L041) — none affect us because we never adopt closed-source as a runtime dependency; we cite or replicate.
- **FRED ToS** (already addressed by R09 substitution) — no fresh blocker in this batch.

Stale / abandoned (do not depend):
- `FRBNY-TimeSeriesAnalysis/Nowcasting` MATLAB — last commit 2019-09 (NY Fed paused the publication 2021–2024 due to structural breaks). We adopt the *statsmodels equivalent* instead.
- `MajesticKhan/Nowcasting-Python` — last commit 2021-02, maintainer "moved away from time series."
- `PyFlux` — abandoned 2017.
- `Pynare`, `PyMacLab`, `DynarePython` — abandoned.
- `Allisterh/Large-BVAR-Python-codes-` — "preliminary testing stage," 4 stars; reference-only.

The single most strategically important finding for L031–L045: **`statsmodels.tsa.statespace.DynamicFactorMQ` is the NY Fed Nowcast spec implemented natively in Python by the author who maintains it at the NY Fed.** This collapses Block I's biggest design risk (the L3 forecast backbone) from "build it ourselves on top of MATLAB references" to "pip install statsmodels." The L3 spine is essentially free.

### L046–L060 open-data-source adoption summary (added)

Top-five new adapters to add to the OPENGEM roster, in priority order:

1. **`opengem-data-wb`** (L046) — World Bank Indicators (live API + WDI archive). The multi-country fallback for any indicator Tier-V doesn't cover. CC-BY GREEN. 16,000 indicators; ~150 pinned for OPENGEM. No auth, generous rate limit.
2. **`opengem-data-imf`** (L047 + L052) — IMF SDMX 3.0 client covering WEO, IFS, DOT (DOTS/IMTS), CPI, COFER as Block I; BOP, IRFCL, FSI, GFS as Block II. The forecast benchmark (WEO) + the bilateral trade panel (DOTS) + the global headline inflation panel (CPI) live here. SDMX 2.1 endpoint is dead — write against 3.0 directly.
3. **`opengem-data-ecb`** (L050) — ECB Data Portal SDMX 2.1. Euro-area depth: EXR, YC, BSI, MIR, ICP, MNA, LFSI, SPF, CISS. CC0 / public-domain. `updatedAfter` + `includeHistory` give a coarse vintage triangle.
4. **`opengem-data-bis`** extended (L049) — Beyond CBPOL, add LBS, CBS, EER, CREDIT_GAPS, TC via bulk SDMX ZIPs. EER unlocks the cross-country REER panel; CREDIT_GAPS is the BIS-canonical early-warning indicator.
5. **`opengem-data-oecd`** (L048) — Live OECD SDMX (EO, QNA, MEI, CLI) parallel to ORDRA's vintage role. EO archive ingestion adds the second forecast comparator after WEO.

Secondary adapters (still ADOPT-NOW for Block I but lower-priority): `opengem-data-trade` (BACI + Comtrade nowcast), `opengem-data-energy` (EIA + OWID), `opengem-data-commodities` (WB Pink Sheet + IMF PCPS), `opengem-data-shipping` (IMF PortWatch), `opengem-data-climate` (NOAA GHCN bulk), `opengem-data-rates-foreign` (Bundesbank / BoE / BoJ / BoC / SNB / RBA), `opengem-data-equities` (Stooq), `opengem-data-crypto` (CoinMetrics community + DeFiLlama + Blockchain.com).

License traps & rate-limit gotchas surfaced across L046–L060:

- **CC-BY-NC trap** on **CoinMetrics Community** (L060), **IEA WEO Free Dataset** (L053), and **PortWatch raw-bulk** (L055, terms similar in spirit) — usable in OPENGEM's free public dashboard, but paid-tier API responses that include these series risk violating the NonCommercial clause. Adapter layer must tag each Observation with `license=cc_by_nc_*` and the API gateway must filter or require explicit per-source paid licensing for the paid tier. **This is the single biggest license risk across the cohort and needs an architectural enforcement pattern**, not just per-adapter checks.
- **IMF SDMX 2.1 → 3.0 migration** (L047) silently bricked half the open-source IMF clients on PyPI/CRAN in early 2025. New adapter must target `api.imf.org/external/sdmx/3.0/`, not the legacy `dataservices.imf.org`. Pin against `~` for latest, not `*`.
- **ECB SDW hostname** `sdw-wsrest.ecb.europa.eu` is dead as of October 2025 (redirects retired). Hardcode `data-api.ecb.europa.eu`.
- **OECD's older `stats.oecd.org` endpoint is deprecated** as of late 2024; new SDMX endpoint is `sdmx.oecd.org/public/rest/`. Old wrappers (CRAN `OECD` package, several Python clients) silently 404.
- **UN Comtrade YELLOW license** prohibits redistributing raw data as bulk; OPENGEM can serve derived aggregates but cannot expose a "download Comtrade as parquet" button. BACI is GREEN and serves that role.
- **Stooq's commercial-redistribution terms unclear** — fine for free public dashboard; would need email clarification for paid tier.
- **yfinance is structurally fragile** — Yahoo periodically tightens throttling and breaks the unofficial scraper. Cannot be a production dependency.
- **NOAA CDO 5 RPS / 10,000 RPD per-token cap** is enforced. GHCN bulk via AWS S3 is the right pattern, not API spot lookups.
- **BIS EER weight rebasing every 3 years** causes apparent retroactive revisions even when underlying FX didn't move. Adapter must record weight vintage.
- **WDI series codes silently rebase base year** (e.g., `NY.GDP.MKTP.KD` has been 1987 / 1995 / 2000 / 2005 / 2010 / 2015 base across vintages). Naive cross-vintage diff conflates revision with rebasing.
- **OECD response cap 1M observations, URL cap 1,000 chars** — easy to hit with wildcarded long-history sweeps. Adapter must chunk.
- **MarineTraffic discontinued credit-based pricing January 2025** — old open-source scripts hitting MarineTraffic with stored API keys now silently fail. Use IMF PortWatch (free) instead.
- **CoinMetrics Community NonCommercial license** is the architectural risk — needs filtering at the API tier layer.

## Notes

- Each loop produces an artifact. No artifact = no completion.
- When new opportunities surface mid-research, add them to the queue rather than blocking.
- Prefer concrete, opinionated outputs over surveys-of-options.
- If stuck on a loop, write a "skipped because" note and move on.
